Parameter tuning, grid search and 10-fold cross validation processes are conducted here.

set.seed(1)

control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
# grid search
glm_grid <- expand.grid(alpha = 1, lambda = c(0, 0.5,1))
dt_grid <- expand.grid(cp = c(0, 0.005,0.01,0.05,0.1))
rf_grid <- expand.grid( mtry = c(5,6,7,8,9,10))
sgb_grid <- expand.grid(n.trees = c(10, 50, 100), shrinkage = c(0.01,0.1), interaction.depth = c(5, 10, 20), n.minobsinnode = 10)

The data is split to test and train data with partition rate “0.8”.

training.data <- data_student_all$class%>%createDataPartition( p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
student_train <- data_student_all[training.data, ]
student_test <- data_student_all[-training.data, ]

Then, all the algorithms are modelled by using the function train.

## regression
glm_model <- train(class ~ ., data = student_train, method = "glmnet", 
                   trControl = control, tuneGrid = glm_grid)
## decision tree
dt_model <- train(class ~ ., data = student_train, method = "rpart", 
                  trControl = control, tuneGrid = dt_grid)
## random forests
rf_model <- train(class ~ ., data = student_train, method = "rf", trControl = control,tuneGrid = rf_grid)

## stochastic gradient boosting
sgb_model <- train(class ~ ., data = student_train, method = "gbm", trControl = control, tuneGrid = sgb_grid)

set.seed(1)

training.communities <- data_communities$ViolentCrimesPerPop %>% createDataPartition(p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_communities<-data_communities[training.communities,]
test_communities<-data_communities[-training.communities,]


x_train_communities<- data.matrix(train_communities[,1:99])
y_train_communities<- train_communities$ViolentCrimesPerPop

x_test_communities<- data.matrix(test_communities[,1:99])
y_test_communities<- test_communities$ViolentCrimesPerPop

Cross-validation results are plotted.

lambdas_to_try <- 10^seq(-3, 5, length.out = 100)
lasso_cv <- cv.glmnet(x_train_communities, as.numeric(y_train_communities), alpha = 1, lambda = lambdas_to_try,
                      standardize = TRUE, nfolds = 10)

lambda_cv <- lasso_cv$lambda.min ## Best cross-validated lambda

plot(lasso_cv)

model_cv <- glmnet(x_train_communities, as.numeric(y_train_communities), alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_cv, standardize = TRUE)
y_hat_cv <- predict(model_cv, x_train_communities)
ssr_cv <- t(as.numeric(y_train_communities) - as.numeric(y_hat_cv)) %*% (as.numeric(y_train_communities) - as.numeric(y_hat_cv))
rsq_lasso_cv <- cor(as.numeric(y_train_communities), y_hat_cv)^2

res <- glmnet(x_train_communities, as.numeric(y_train_communities), alpha = 1, lambda = lambdas_to_try, standardize = FALSE)


plot(res, xvar = "lambda")

This graph shows how increasing lambda shrinks the coefficients.Each line shows coefficients for one variables, for different lambdas.The higher the lambda, the more the coefficients are shrinked towards zero.

set.seed(105)

regression_tree <- function(i,j){
  tree<-rpart(Class~.,data = communities_train,control = rpart.control(minbucket=i,cp=j),method = "anova")
  rpart.plot(tree,box.palette = "RdBu",shadow.col = "gray",nn=TRUE)
  plotcp(tree)
  pred<-predict(tree,communities_test)
  
  rss <- sum((pred - communities_test$Class) ^ 2)  
  tss <- sum(((communities_test$Class) - mean(communities_test$Class)) ^ 2)
  rsq <- 1 - (rss/tss)
  print(rsq)
}
one <- regression_tree(1,0.01)

set.seed(105)

rf <- function(i){
  rf<-randomForest(Class~.,data=communities_train,proximity=TRUE,mtry=i)
  plot(rf)
  
  pred<-predict(rf,communities_test)

  rss <- sum((pred - communities_test$Class) ^ 2)  
  tss <- sum((communities_test$Class - mean(communities_test$Class)) ^ 2) 
  rsq <- 1 - (rss/tss)
  print(rsq)
}
